06375nam a22008775i 9780824841577DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20032003hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248415777 a10.1515/97808248415772doi  a(DE-B1597)483969  a(OCoLC)1013946422  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aNX180.F4bG44 2003 7aART0000002bisacsh00aGender and Power in the Japanese Visual Field /ced. by Joshua S. Mostow, Maribeth Graybill, Norman Bryson. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b108 illus., 8 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Gender in Japanese Art -- t3. The Image of Women in Battle Scenes: “Sexually” Imprinted Bodies -- t4. The Gender of Wakashu and the Grammar of Desire -- t5. Marketing Desire: Advertising and Sexuality in Edo Literature, Drama, and Art -- t6.Westernizing Bodies: Women, Art, and Power in Meiji Yāga -- t7. Icons of Femininity: Japanese National Painting and the Paradox of Modernity -- t8. Images of Women in National Art Exhibitions during the Korean Colonial Period -- t9. The Otherness of Women in the Avant-Garde Film Woman in the Dunes -- t10. Gender in Contemporary Japanese Art -- t11. Busty Battlin’ Babes: The Evolution of the Shōjo in 1990s Visual Culture -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this, the first collection in English of feminist-oriented research on Japanese art and visual culture, an international group of scholars examines representations of women in a wide range of visual work. The volume begins with Chino Kaori's now-classic essay "Gender in Japanese Art," which introduced feminist theory to Japanese art. This is followed by a closer look at a famous thirteenth-century battle scroll and the production of bijin (beautiful women) prints within the world of Edo-period advertising. A rare homoerotic picture-book is used to extrapolate the "grammar of desire" as represented in late seventeenth-century Edo. In the modern period, contributors consider the introduction to Meiji Japan of the Western nude and oil-painting and examine Nihonga (Japanese-style painting) and the role of one of its famous artists. The book then shifts its focus to an examination of paintings produced for the Japanese-sponsored annual salons held in colonial Korea. The postwar period comes under scrutiny in a study of the novel Woman in the Dunes and its film adaptation. The critical discourse that surrounded women artists of the late twentieth-century--the "Super Girls of Art"--is analyzed, followed by a consideration of gender ambiguity and cross-gender identification in contemporary anime and manga. Contributors: Grunhild Borggreen, Norman Bryson, Chino Kaori, Doris Croissant, Ikeda Shinobu, Kim Hye-shin, Chigusa Kimura-Steven, Joshua S. Mostow, Sharalyn Orbaugh, David Pollack.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArts, Japanese. 0aFeminism and the artszJapan. 0aGender identity in art. 0aWomen in art. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 aBorggreen, Gunhild, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryson, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryson, Norman, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCroissant, Doris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraybill, Maribeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHyeshin, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaori, Chino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator